<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-292-467  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 292 467.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  Jan 25 1989 n1101* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Dataflight offers &quot;the first&quot; full text database for OS-2.andO;(Dataflight Software Inc.) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Dataflight Software Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Concordance Information Retrieval System (Data base managementsystem) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionData Base Management SystemsOS-2.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>DATAFLIGHT OFFERS &quot;THE FIRST&quot; FULL TEXT DATABASE FOR OS/2 In what it claimsis the only full-text database for the new operating system, DataflightSoftware Inc is shipping an OS/2 version of its Concordance InformationRetrieval System.andP;  The Los Angeles-based firm says that by using Boolean,relational, and proximity searches, any word, phrase or combin-ation of thetwo can extracted from its database.andP;  The new version uses files that areinterchangeable with the original MS-DOS version, but offers a number of newfeatures.andP;  According to Dataflight, these include the indexing of largedatabases at twice the speed of the MS-DOS version, and support formulti-user and networked systems.andP;  The new version also enables users toaccess library-sized Concordance databases as desktop accessories.andP;  Otherfea-tures include support for fixed-9gth and free text fields and theprovision of search-management, text-import, -loading, -unloading, andon-line context-sensitive-help facilities.andP;  A report writer, text editor, anddatabase and stopword dictionaries, together with a macro language toautomate searches, are also available.andP;  The product can run on AT-alikes orPS/2s, and on 80x88-based micros with a hard disk and Version 1.0 or above ofOS/2.andP;  Concordance databases can reside on any kind of disk medium, theproduct is not copy protected and comes on 5.25&quot; or 3.5&quot; floppies - thesuggested US price is $500.andO;</TEXT></DOC>